I agree it is extremely hard to see a child suffering. However, there are children who struggle with depressive thoughts and anxiety, etc. even when there *isn't* a pandemic going on. I'm not sure why there's an assumption that kids naturally don't have mental health problems.

Remote school is not the thing causing your child's isolation. COVID is the thing causing it, and it needs to actually be stopped in a meaningful way, not just accepted as yet another horrible thing we must endure forever.

Fwiw I think I still did a pretty decent job all things considered; I just feel like I could have coped even better if I'd known from the start, and that it would have made things easier on both of us. 😔

I know hindsight is 20/20, but I really do think I would have been able to cope a lot better with the demands of having a newborn/toddler and not have come out of it so traumatized if I'd known what was going on and how to find the right kind of help.

Being able to understand your child's difficulties is very good. It means you can really *get* where they're coming from and have a good idea of how to help them BUT it doesn't magically make your own sensory issues, emotional regulation problems or meltdown triggers go away.

Meanwhile, people either don't know how or can't properly shovel and sand their walks because why the fuck would you buy a snow shovel or salt when it snows like once a year?? And when you actually need onez they're all sold out anyway.

Add to this the fact that this sort of weather (snowing AND very low temps) is (or used to be) unusual so there's only infrastructure to plow and sand a few key roads for short weather events, and you get WA shutting down for  what the Midwest sees as a run of the mill snow storm

There's nothing special about the way snow or ice forms in the PNW, it's just that temps aren't below freezing when snow starts falling here (and a lot of the time it turns from rain to snow), so when it starts to stick you already have a layer of solid ice under it.

Know where your main shut off valve is. If you get a burst pipe and all else fails, you can shut off the water to your whole house. (But if you haven't touched it since you moved in a decade ago, don't test it until you need it because it seize up and cause more problems 😬)

If at some point you go to use a faucet during a cold snap and you only get a trickle of water--DON'T PANIC. Leave the faucet on and try to figure out where the blockage is. You can gently thaw pipes with a hair dryer, an electric blanket or rags soaked in warm water.

When temps will be in the 20s or lower multiple nights, open any cabinets around pipes on the outside walls of your home at night to let warm air circulate more freely. Set a faucet that's far away from your main supply line (upstairs sink, for example) to drip slowly overnight.

If you don't have shut offs for your outdoor spigots, still disconnect hoses but TURN ON the faucets to let them to drip very slowly on sub 20° nights. Running water doesn't freeze as easily and will prevent bursting pipes by letting water flow for as long as possible.

First, disconnect outdoor hoses from spigots (drain the hoses too--you'll thank yourself if you need to use them before it thaws). If you're lucky and have newer spigots there may be a shut off valve 1-2' inside your crawlspace/basement for each one. Turn these off & drain.
